\section{Overview x}

\begin{itemize}
\item {\bf Source Verse} (\Cref{fig:source-verse-expr,fig:source-verse-expr2}) is (an approximation of) the full source language.
\item The \emph{superficial-desugar} pass desugars
(\Cref{fig:sv-to-sv-1,fig:sv-to-sv-2}) Source Verse into
  {\bf Essential Verse} (\Cref{fig:small-source-verse}), whose distinctive feature is TimLambdas.
  Essential Verse is a subset of Source Verse.
\item A \emph{wrapping transformation} (\Cref{fig:mini-verse}) further
desugars Essential Verse into {\bf Mini Verse}
(\Cref{fig:mini-verse}). \emph{BCP: Why is the figure labeled Plan C?}
\item A \emph{translation for verification and execution}
(\Cref{fig:ds12})
takes Mini Verse to {\bf Core Verse} (\Cref{fig:core-verse}).  The
operational semantics of Core Verse in terms of rewrite and
verification rules is defined in \Crefrange{fig:vc-syntax}{fig:verifier-rules-arrays}
(\emph{BCP: As of July 2025, Simon says \Cref{fig:vc-contexts} is out of date}).
\item From here, we have three different approaches to the denotational semantics
  of Core Verse: \emph{BCP: These still need figure numbers...}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Plan A: a direct denotational semantics
    (\Crefrange{fig:den-sem1}{fig:den-sem-dest1}---as of July 2025,
    Lennart is just starting on this)
  \item Plan B: desugar into {\bf Destination Passing Style Verse}
    (DpsVerse), then give a semantics to that.
  \item Plan C: desugar into {\bf Mini Verse}, still in expression
    style, and give a semantics to that.
  \end{itemize}
\item The rewrite rules
\item The verification rules
\end{itemize}

